g.title: Folded Corner.138
g.desc: A Virtual Proxy creates the ‘real’ subject on demand, so when...

g.text: A Virtual Proxy creates the ‘real’ subject on demand, so when the subject is ‘indispensable’. The Virtual Proxy encapsulates the real subject and follows the same interface as the real object. Clients will create the Proxy via the subject interface, not knowing that the real subject is not created yet. Virtual proxies can handle some simple requests where the real subject is not required yet (=caching). Advantages of the Virtual Proxy are performance and memory optimization. Performance, because certain ‘expensive’ objects are not created directly during start-up. This optimizes boot-up time. This is at the expense of runtime performance, because these objects still need to be created when required. However, the initialization time of the objects is more distributed and some objects might not even be needed. Memory optimization, because these ‘expensive’ objects are not directly loaded into RAM when the application starts. There might be scenarios that these objects don’t need to be created at all.

g.title: Folded Corner.205
g.desc: The Proxy pattern compliments Single Responsibility and there...

g.text: The Proxy pattern compliments Single Responsibility and therefore Open Closed. Extracting Remote, Virtual and Protection responsibilities into a separate Proxy object, instead of residing that logic inside the client or subject, enhances flexibility of extending without modifying. It is possible to change / ‘swap’ the Proxy while not having to change the client nor subject. This improves stability of the code base. The same accounts when the subject is already an existing instance in the code base. The Proxy wraps around the existing subject and possible regression is reduced. Additionally, the Proxy follows the same interface as the subject. This means clients don’t notice working with a Proxy or working with the actual object. Again maintenance reduction on client-side.

g.title: Folded Corner.212
g.desc: Remote proxies are often used for client-server communication...

g.text: Remote proxies are often used for client-server communication. The client wants to use an object on the server-side. The clients requires network calls and connection maintenance , because the object is located in a different address space. A Proxy provides this ‘networking’, while following the same interface as the remote object. I.e. client uses Proxy object functionality, proxy encodes this into a network call, server proxy decodes the network call, remote object gets called. The remote Proxy is useful, because client does not need to worry about networking details.

g.title: Folded Corner.216
g.desc: A protection Proxy provides restricted access to the original...

g.text: A protection Proxy provides restricted access to the original object. Different access Proxies provide different restrictions to the original object. Each of these Proxies encapsulate the same real subject, but with limited access. E.g. multiple clients can have access to a shared drive, but a Proxy limits certain user to only read or read & write. E.g. a coffee shop provides access to the internet via a https Proxy. Internet clients cannot visit gabling websites, because the https Proxy denies these web requests. A protection Proxy might also fulfill thread-safety to an existing object.

g.title: Folded Corner.226
g.desc: The Proxy pattern compliments Single Responsibility principle...

g.text: The Proxy pattern compliments Single Responsibility principle. Proxy extracts access constraints from client and subject side. A remote Proxy performs networking and is a responsibility on its own. This logic shouldn’t reside in the client directly, because this minimizes testability, reusability and readability of the client code. The responsibility of a virtual Proxy shouldn’t reside in client nor subject code, as for the same reasons. The if-conditions to postpone object creation will increase cyclomatic complexity of the client or subject code. As stated proxies enhance testability, reusability and readability. Testability, because we can test proxies in isolation. This results in earlier feedback and faster pin-pointing why the software malfunctions as in contrast to adding this functionality to client or subject directly. Reusability, because we can re-use proxies across multiple clients. Readability, because logic is separated into ‘logical’ blocks. This enhances change and extension.

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The protection Proxy could prevent calls when the user is not...

g.text: The protection Proxy could prevent calls when the user is not authorized. This means the protection Proxy is dependent on an interface function it cannot fulfil. I.e. violation of interface segregation principle. It could mean that the proxy ‘resolves’ this by rising a not ‘prohibited’ exception. This results in exception handling on client-side. Another option is to do nothing at all, this means the Proxy should change along when the uninterested interface function signature changes.
